MATH 140: Using ggplot

Hitchman

In some R activities you will be asked to produce graphics using ggplot2, a nice graphics package in R. In this tutorial we focus on three types of graphics: histograms, scatter plots, and box plots.

I encourage you to replicate all the graphs in this tutorial in your own RStudio session.

In order to produce graphics with ggplot2, you need to load it into your RStudio session. The ggplot2 package is part of the tidyverse package, so begin your session by loading the tidyverse. Recall, do do this, run the line

library(tidyverse)

With the tidyverse loaded, you are ready to use the ggplot functions for generating graphs.

All the plots in this tutorial use the Old Faithful data set that comes built-in to the RStudio program.

With the code below, you can load the data into your session with the working name df (short for data frame). The code below also displays the first eight rows of the data frame, to help familiarize yourself with the data set. The data set records information about \(n = 272\) eruptions of the Old Faithful geyser. The eruptions variable indicates how long the eruption lasted (in minutes), and the waiting variable indicates how long the wait was until the next eruption (in minutes).

df <- faithful
head(df,8)
##   eruptions waiting
## 1     3.600      79
## 2     1.800      54
## 3     3.333      74
## 4     2.283      62
## 5     4.533      85
## 6     2.883      55
## 7     4.700      88
## 8     3.600      85

Code for plots with the ggplot package will have this general look:

ggplot(data = ..., aes(x = ... , y= ... , etc.)) +
  [plot type, with options in parentheses] + 
  [other layer, such as plot title] + 
  [other layer, such as a plot theme, or axis label]+
  [other layer]+...

Two remarks before showing many examples.

  1. We need a + sign at the end of each line if we plan to add another layer. The last line should not end with a + sign.
  2. We specify variables involved in a plot within the aes() command, aes being short for aesthetic. The dots and lines in plots have certain locations, colors, shapes, and sizes. In ggplot, these features are called aesthetics.

Histograms with ggplot

Use geom_histogram(), and specify x inside aes().

Basic Histogram

ggplot(data = df, aes(x=waiting)) +
  geom_histogram()

Specify the bins

Specifying the bins for a histogram is good practice. You can either specify the bin widths with the binwidth option inside the geom_histogram() command, or you can specify the total number of bins with the bins option.

Using binwidth option

In the following graph, each bin has width 4.

ggplot(data = df, aes(x=waiting)) +
  geom_histogram(binwidth = 4)

Using the bins option

In the following plot we create 20 equal width bins

ggplot(data = df, aes(x=waiting)) +
  geom_histogram(bins = 20)

Add color and axis labels

ggplot(data = df,aes(x=waiting)) +
  geom_histogram(binwidth = 2,col="blue",fill="yellow") + 
  xlab("time between eruptions (min)") + 
  ggtitle("Histogram of Old Faithful Wait Times")

The col option colors the boundary of each bar, the fill option colors the interior of each bar. If we want to change the y-axis label, we use the code ylab("enter new label here inside quotes").

Change the theme

If youre not a fan of the gray plot background, you can change the theme. Here are two other options:

ggplot(data = df,aes(x=waiting)) +
  geom_histogram(binwidth = 2, col="blue", fill="yellow") + 
  xlab("time between eruptions (min)") + 
  ggtitle("Histogram of Old Faithful Wait Times") + 
  theme_classic()

ggplot(data = df,aes(x=eruptions)) +
  geom_histogram(bins = 20, col="white", fill="dodgerblue") + 
  xlab("Eruption duration (min)") + 
  ggtitle("Histogram of Old Faithful Eruption Durations") + 
  theme_bw()

Notice in this last plot I changed from binwidths to specifying the number of bins. By the way, I really like the color dodgerblue even though Im not a big Dodgers fan.

Bonus Round - Density Plot

Instead of a histogram of counts, we can produce a histogram of relative frequencies by adding the option aes(y = ..density..) as below. This will produce a histogram that records the proportion of the values falling in each bin, not the total counts.

ggplot(df, aes(x=eruptions)) + 
  geom_histogram(aes(y = ..density..), bins=20, col="white", fill="dodgerblue",alpha = 0.4)

We remark that the alpha option above refers to the opacity of the fill color. Values of alpha range from 0 to 1, with lower values corresponding to more transparent colors. So in this plot the dodgerblue color has been made more transparent. If we had set alpha = 1, the color would look as it did in the previous histogram.

ggplot(df, aes(x=eruptions)) + 
  geom_density() + 
  geom_vline(aes(xintercept=mean(eruptions)),
            color="blue", linetype="dashed", size=1)

The geom_density() function gives an idealized density plot rather than a histogram.

The geom_vline() option above was thrown in just for fun. It places a vertical line in the graph, for which weve specified these options: the color is blue, it is dashed, and it hits the x-axis at the mean value of the eruptions. This distribution is clearly bimodal!!

Scatter Plots with ggplot

Use the geom_point() plot type command, and specify x and y inside aes().

Basic scatter plot

ggplot(data = df,aes(x=waiting,y=eruptions)) +
  geom_point()

Add color and axis labels

ggplot(data = df,aes(x=waiting,y=eruptions)) +
  geom_point(col="seagreen")+
  xlab("time between eruptions (min)") + 
  ylab("eruption duration (min)") +
  ggtitle("Old Faithful") + 
  theme_bw()

Seagreen! I like it!

R has lots (657) of built-in color names. You can see the names in RStudio if you run colors().

Add color by category

For the purposes of illustrating the power of ggplot, lets add a categorical variable to the data frame called letter that randomly assigns to each observation the letter a, b, or c.

df$letter = sample(c("a","b","c"),nrow(df),replace=TRUE)
head(df,10)
##    eruptions waiting letter
## 1      3.600      79      c
## 2      1.800      54      c
## 3      3.333      74      c
## 4      2.283      62      a
## 5      4.533      85      b
## 6      2.883      55      a
## 7      4.700      88      a
## 8      3.600      85      b
## 9      1.950      51      b
## 10     4.350      85      b

We can color points in a scatter plot according to a categorical variable by specifying col = this variable within the aes() command.

ggplot(data = df,aes(x=waiting,y=eruptions,col=letter)) +
  geom_point()+
  xlab("time between eruptions (min)") + 
  ylab("eruption duration (min)") + 
  ggtitle("Old Faithful") + 
  theme_bw()

Bonus Round - Fit the line

We have two ways to add a line to a plot in ggplot.

Using geom_abline()

The first approach is to add the line by specifying the slope and y-intercept using geom_abline(slope = , intercept = ).

For instance, the slope and \(y\)-intercept for the least squares line in the faithful example are 0.07563 and -1.87402, respectively (found by using the code `lm(eruptions~waiting,df)).

Knowing these values we can add a line to a scatter plot by having two layers in our plot: a geom_point layer which plots the points, and a geom_abline layer which plots the line.

ggplot(data = df,aes(x=waiting,y=eruptions)) +
  geom_point()+
  geom_abline(slope = 0.07563, intercept = -1.87402)

We can add color to layers separately, we can change the size of the points and the size of the line, we can change the linetype in the geom_abline() layer, and we can add labels to give appropriate details:

ggplot(data = df,aes(x=waiting,y=eruptions)) +
  geom_point(col="seagreen",size=.5)+
  geom_abline(slope = 0.07563, intercept = -1.87402,col="blue",linetype="dashed",size=.7)+
  xlab("time between eruptions (min)") + 
  ylab("eruption duration (min)") +
  ggtitle("Old Faithful")

Using geom_smooth()

The second approach to fitting a line to data is to use the geom_smooth()command. Heres how to add the least squares regression line to the scatter plot:

ggplot(data = df,aes(x=waiting, y = eruptions)) +
  geom_point() +
  geom_smooth(method='lm', formula=y~x) +
  theme_bw()

The gray bar of varying thickness surrounding the least squares regression line is called a confidence band, something we wont consider here. To remove it from a plot, add the se = FALSE option in your geom_smooth() line. While were at it, lets spruce up the look of it all:

ggplot(data = df,aes(x=waiting, y = eruptions)) +
  geom_point() +
  geom_smooth(method='lm', formula=y~x, col="blue",size=.8,se=FALSE) +
  xlab("time between eruptions (min)") + 
  ylab("eruption duration (min)") + 
  ggtitle("Old Faithful data with least squares regression line") + 
  theme_bw()

Box plots with ggplot

Basic box plot

Use the geom_boxplot() plot type command.

ggplot(data = df,aes(x=waiting)) +
  geom_boxplot() +
  xlab("time (min)") + 
  ggtitle("Waiting time between eruptions")

This plot is unsatisfying because it gives values on the y-axis, which are meaningless in the context of this box plot. We can hide them:

ggplot(data = df,aes(x=waiting)) +
  geom_boxplot() +
  xlab("time (min)") + 
  ylab(" ") + 
  ggtitle("Waiting time between eruptions")+
  theme(axis.ticks.y = element_blank(),
        axis.text.y = element_blank())

This code is cumbersome, but it gets the job done.

Side-by-side box plots

The package ggplot makes nice side-by-side box plots quite easily.

If \(x\) is a numerical variable and \(y\) is a categorical variable, we can determine side-by-side box plots for the values of \(x\) grouped by the values of \(y\).

ggplot(data = df,aes(x=waiting,y=letter)) +
  geom_boxplot() +
  xlab("time (min)") + 
  ylab("letter") + 
  ggtitle("Waiting time between eruptions")

Since the letters a, b, and c were assigned at random to the different eruptions, it is not surprising that the box plots for each letter type are roughly the same.

Coloring box plots

We can fill box plots with color according to a categorical variable using the fill option.

ggplot(data = df,aes(x=waiting,y=letter,fill=letter)) +
  geom_boxplot() +
  xlab("time (min)") + 
  ylab("letter") + 
  ggtitle("Waiting time between eruptions")

Hiding the legend

We can hide the legend if it is superfluous, as it is above, by adding show.legend = FALSE inside the geom_boxplot() command.

ggplot(data = df,aes(x=waiting,y=letter,fill=letter)) +
  geom_boxplot(show.legend = FALSE) +
  xlab("time (min)") + 
  ylab("letter") + 
  ggtitle("Waiting time between eruptions")

Customizing colors

ggplot(data = df,aes(x=waiting,y=letter)) +
  geom_boxplot(fill=c("pink","brown3","orange")) +
  xlab("time (min)") + 
  ylab("letter") + 
  ggtitle("Waiting time between eruptions")

Note: Since the categorical variable letter has 3 different values, we specify 3 different colors in the geom_boxplot() command, and these colors are expressed as a vector (inside the c() method).

Bonus Round - Color Opacity

As mentioned in the histogram section, the alpha option adjusts the opacity of a color in a plot. The closer alpha is to 0, the more transparent it becomes, and the closer to 1, the more opaque it becomes. In the graph below the three box plots are all filled with the color orange but with different alpha values.

ggplot(data = df,aes(x=waiting,y=letter)) +
  geom_boxplot(fill="orange", alpha=c(.2, .6, .9)) +
  xlab("time (min)") + 
  ylab("letter") + 
  ggtitle("Waiting time between eruptions")

Bonus plot - bar plot for categorical variable

In Base R we can visualize the frequencies for a categorical variable as follows:

barplot(table(df$letter))

We can also create a bar plot with gglplot with the following code:

ggplot(data=df,aes(x=letter))+
  geom_bar(stat="count")

And we can add color, change bar width, and add labels as usual. We can also speficy the limits of the values on the y-axis to be, say, 0 to 100:

ggplot(data=df,aes(x=letter))+
  geom_bar(stat="count", width=.5, fill=c("steelblue","wheat","tomato"))+
  ylim(0,100)+
  ggtitle("Number of eruptions by letter")+
  theme_classic()
